<font face=Verdana size=4>

</font><h1><font face=Verdana size=4><b>LLLT </b><span style=font-weight:400><font size=4>= <b>Low Level 

Light Therapy</b> </font></span></font></h1>

<p><font face=Verdana size=2>LLLT stimulates the repair or reduction of pain 

of a wide variety of body parts. </font></p><font face=Verdana size=2>

<p>One of the many other names (<a href=#AssociatedNames>see below</a>) for LLLT is Cold Laser. It is ‘cold’ 

because the lasers/LEDs are so dim that they do not heat up tissue. Note: I can 

just barely notice a temperature increase when I shine my 1 watt LED flashlight 

on my lips. I am not able to feel 20 milliwatts emitted by our LLLT – however 

many <a href=#Horse%20links>horses</a> can sense LLLT.</p>

<p>In early 2008 I discovered LLLT and then researched the topic on the internet and 

thru medical publications.  <br>

LLLT appeared to be an excellent solution for my wife's lymphoedema. <br>

We did not want to pay many thousands of dollars to a set of LLLT treatments 

which would provide relief for perhaps 6 months.<br>

I designed an LLLT based on the best research I could find. <br>

There are 20+ parameters for LLLT, including wavelength, power output, number of 

treatments per week, frequency of dark periods, length of dark periods, etc.<br>

We have been amazed at the results, what we have to call magic LLLT on not only 

lymphoedema, but also for many other ailments, including her 60 year old ankle 

pain which disappeared after a single LLLT session.  Have been using it 

since Aug 2008</p>

<p><a href=#Update><b>U</b></a><b><a href=#Update>pdates at end of this page</a>  

with description of model 2.0</b></p>

</font>

<font face=Verdana><i><b>

<p>Our Success</p>

</b></i></font><font face=Verdana size=2>

<p>My LLLT design took 6 months to design, construct, and debug.  It can is 

basically an improvement on that made in Australia. <br>

<a href=http://www.riancorp.com/>http://www.riancorp.com/</a> makes the only 

Laser which the FDA has approved for lymphoedema<br>

<a href="http://www.google.com/url?sa=t&amp;source=web&amp;ct=res&amp;cd=1&amp;url=http://services.bepress.com/context/eci/tissue_regen/article/1015/type/native/viewcontent/&amp;ei=UnXTSKWzM6SmpwT6sZipDg&amp;usg=AFQjCNHRSWORYaThCBuqq0h577FFsziRDw&amp;sig2=szFwRUw2mVul">

Excellent power-point summary of the Australian LLLT</a><br>

<a href="http://www.lymphnotes.com/bb/showthread.php?s=ebd031c20806950cfcd57767782a5ae2&amp;threadid=486">

Lymphoema forum 2007 discussion on Riancorp</a> LLLT</p>

<p><b>Similar:</b> Wavelength = 905 angstrom, Laser diode, 5 watts peak output 

IR per each diode, Applied to lymph area for 1 minute<br>

5,000 pulses per second – thus applying about 300,000 pulses in 1 minute</p>

<p><b>Different: </b><br>

1) Use 4 Laser diodes instead of 1, <br>

2) Diodes are positioned about 1" above the skin <br>

– so as to allow spreading to cover about 40% of the area with the 4 

diodes instead of 2% of the area with the single diode on the skin. <br>

This spreading reduces the peak power per sq. cm. at the skin to 

about 1/20.<br>

3) Treatment area, with about 40% of it illuminated, is 12 sq cm at the skin 

surface, <br>

which is 60X larger total area and 24X larger illuminated area than 

the 0.2 sq. cm for commercial single Laser Diode.<br>

4) Cannot press the Laser Diodes into tissue, so as to minimize the light loss 

in fatty tissue.<br>

<a name=DarkTimes>5) Included 20 "dark times" of 1/10 second each during the 1 minute.

</a> <br>

{Tina Karu: Ten Lectures on Basic Science of Laser 

Phototherapy – page 69 shows 2X increased attachment with "dark times of 1/10 

second. <br>

So we thought that we would include "dark times" in our 

design. <br>

We intuitively feel that while the body cannot respond to changes 

in light at the rate of 5,000 per second, <br>

there is a possibility of the body responding to 1/10 second dark 

times every 3 seconds. <br>

Perhaps coherent laser speckle produces a modulation of the light 

better than what we use.}<br>

6) Have LLLT just before having a lymph massage and then go to sleep.</p>

<p><a href=http://www.laser.nu/lllt/lllt_editorial.htm>

http://www.laser.nu/lllt/lllt_editorial.htm</a>  from 2003 has a good list 

of the many parameter for LLLT.  Scroll down to "Why laser therapy fails - 

and succeeds" </p>

<p>I do not expect the <a href=http://www.riancorp.com/>company in Australia</a> 

to improve their LLLT since they have just spent $250,000 on a clinical double 

blind trial to prove the device and the protocol to the US FDA (and regulatory 

agencies in other countries) They irradiate 17 points for 1 minute 3 days a 

week. After 3 weeks their point laser will likely have irradiated every lymph 

node in the area. Ours irradiates all lymph nodes in a 12 sq cm area in a single 

minute.</p>

<p><b>Laser is not a magic cure for lymphedema<br>

</b>For your information; From practical experience and statistical information 

laser therapy is best when used with other lymphatic drainage therapies. <br>

It is not a magic cure to control lymphedema. </p>

<p><b>What laser has the potential to do for lymphedema</b><br>

Laser will assist in improving lymphatic flow and softening hard fibrotic 

tissues. This in turn normally will help to reduce the associated swelling of 

lymphedema. </p>

<p>Laser normally works faster with arm lymphedema than with leg lymphedema. </p>

<p>The results of laser therapy can be truly amazing. <br>

Some people respond quickly after just one 60 minute session. <br>

With other people it may take many applications to have a similar effect and 

provide the desired result. </p>

<p>Recorded information and statistics indicate Laser treatment is ongoing. <br>

If no other therapy is concurrently combined into a lymphedema treatment 

regimen, then laser therapy is often required every 2-3 weeks for a one hour 

session. </p>

<p>Given the requirement of ongoing treatment i<b>t becomes cost effective to 

purchase a hand held laser for self administration or share among 3 or 4 people 

living nearby</b> suburbs where the laser may be used at home. </p>

<p>Laser therapy for treating lymphedema works best when combined with Complex 

Physical (lymphatic) Therapy (CPT). CPT consists of lymphatic drainage massage, 

self massage, compression bandaging, compression garments, skin care and eating 

the best choice foods to promote lymphatic health with dietary considerations.

</p>

<h2>How Low Level Laser Therapy Works <span style=font-weight:400>(by a 

Chiropractor)</span></h2>

</font><font face=Arial size=2>

<p></p>

</font><font face=Verdana size=2>

<p>Low Level Lasers are also called (Cold lasers) because there is no heat 

produced with this type of device, unlike the lasers used in surgeries. These 

lasers increase cellular energy and help produce faster cellular activities like 

cell reproduction and regeneration. The laser stimulates an increase in cellular 

mitochondrial ATP production, which enhances and moderates cell activity. The 

cold laser has a positive influence on cell proliferation, immune cell function 

and the lymphatic and vascular systems. The result is greatly improved wound and 

injury healing, in dramatically less time. </p>

</font><font face=Arial size=2>

<p></p>

<font face=Verdana size=2>

<p>The effects produced by the laser are anti-inflammatory in response, reducing 

edema and acute swelling. Circulation and cellular metabolism is elevated in the 

treated area, thus reducing pain, increasing range of motion and improving 

overall mobility. The therapy also can decrease the sensations of pain 

experienced by nerves, and increases the energy in the cells, which stimulates 

them to replicate and heal at a much faster rate. </p>

<p>Cold lasers have been proven effective in reducing both acute and chronic 

pain. These laser have been used for a variety of health issues with great 

success. The Erchonia medical laser was the first Low Level Laser manufacturer 

to be given FDA approved marketing clearance for use in Pain Therapy for 

treatment of chronic neck and shoulder pain. </p>

<h3>My concept of LLLT mechanisms - circa 2008</h3>

<p>I feel that the body is very used to receiving IR illumination from the sun - 

for example see

<a href=http://www.henrylahore.com/DOCUME~1/HENRYL~1/LOCALS~1/Temp/FrontPageTempDir/www.easthorse.net/cm/images/spectrum.gif>

<font face=Arial size=2 color=#0000ff><u>

www.easthorse.net/cm/images/spectrum.gif</u></font></a><font face=Arial size=2>

<br>

The if we guess that the body can not distinguish 'color' differences of 100nm, 

then the IR from the sun is about 7X stronger than our probe,<br>

thus if LLLT were purely an intensity effect, 7 minutes of the sun should 

provide the same effect as 1 minute of our LLLT probe.<br>

Since most animal bodies have evolved to be used to the sun, I am inclined to 

think that the LLLT effect is not purely a photo effect, but due to dark to 

light transitions.<br>

Karu's tests on very simple life forms found that the best effect came from 

having 1/10 second dark periods.<br>

The dark to light <font face=Arial size=2>transitions </font>gets the 

attention of the body - perhaps creating heat stress proteins or later sending 

stem cells to that part of the body.<br>

Coherent lasers naturally produce light intensity variations - which are called 

speckles.  <br>

Since we do not use coherent lasers, we try to get a similar 

effect by modulating the light electrically.<br>

It might also be that the body grows and then sends the repair troops to the 

body parts which both have the dark to light <font face=Arial size=2>

transitions </font>and are 'hurting'.</font></p>

<h2>Wavelengths</h2>

<p>Wavelengths in the 600-700-nm range <font color=#FF0000><b>(RED)</b></font> 

are chosen for treating superficial tissue, <br>

and wavelengths between 780 and 950 are chosen for deeper-seated tissues due to 

longer optical penetration distances through tissue. </p>

<p>GaAlAs lasers emit 800-830 nm light and GaAs lasers emit 904nm (what we used)</p>

<h1>Design and protocol of our LLLT</h1>

</b></i></font><font face=Verdana size=2><b>

</b></font><p><font face=Verdana size=2><b>HEAD1: <u>average intensity</u> per diode = 5 milliwatts</b></font><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana>. </font></font></p><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana>

</font><font face=Verdana size=2><b>

</b></font><p><font face=Verdana size=2><b><a name=illumination></a>4 Laser Diodes</b></font><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana> 

each of which can emit a <b><u>peak intensity</u> of</b> <b>5 watts</b> 

(reported lymph research uses 1 Laser diode with a peak intensity of 5 watts. 

The laser diodes I am getting could actually put out 25 watts, but I will have 

it restrained to put out a maximum of 5 watts. Note: the peak power of the laser 

determines the depth of penetration into the tissue. 5 watts may get as deep as 

2 cm. We will have a possibility of getting even deeper in the future if we wish 

to increase the peak intensity – but at the risk of giving the surface too much 

illumination.</font></font></p><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana>

</font><font face=Verdana size=2><b>

</b></font><p><font face=Verdana size=2><b>Provide 2 joules of illumination per square cm per each treatment</b></font><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana>. 

Identical to reported lymphedema research. Also, many other LLLT research papers 

have good results only when using illumination of between ½ joule and 2 joules 

per sq. cm.</font></font></p><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana>

</font><font face=Verdana size=2><b>

</b></font><p><font face=Verdana size=2><b>Wavelength 905 nm</b></font><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana> 

Researchers have used 890 nm and 904 nm. Tissues appear to let any light thru 

(window) which has a wavelength of between 800 nm and 1300 nm. One journal 

article on mechanisms of light interaction with tissue has a graph derived from 

several researchers including Karu – the author of the book I have ordered, that 

the "action spectrum" (wavelengths which actually produce some action in cells) 

has two peaks: Peak 1 with an action = 2 @ 820 nm and Peak 2 with an action 

spectrum = 1.8 @ 870-930 nm. The valley (region of least action) at 850 nm 

between the two peaks has an action spectrum of only 0.2. The Laser Diode for 

Head1 operates near the top of the second peak of the "action spectrum". (Note – 

I almost had ordered a Laser with a 850 nm wavelength, which would have had the 

worst "action spectrum")</font></font></p><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana>

</font><font face=Verdana size=2><b>

</b></font><p><font face=Verdana size=2><b>Pulse Rate: 5,000 per second</b></font><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana> 

(= 200,000 nanoseconds): identical to reported research. </font></font></p><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana>

</font><font face=Verdana size=2><b>

</b></font><p><font face=Verdana size=2><b>Duty Cycle (% on time) = 0.1%</b></font><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana> 

Some people believe that a short intense pulse provides a pumping action to the 

cell – a light pulse of this intensity apparently only heats a cell up by 1/100 

of a degree, which apparently provides equivalent of about 1 atmosphere of 

pressure. It is well documented that Laser Therapy does increase cell 

permeability – increasing the flow of Calcium and Potassium thru the cell 

membrane among many other things.</font></font></p><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana>

</font><font face=Verdana size=2><b>

</b></font><p><font face=Verdana size=2><b>Separate two blocks of treatment by 6 weeks</b></font><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana>. 

Both of the lymphedema LLLT reports in the literature <br>

1) treat for 3 weeks, 2) wait for 6 weeks, 3) treat for a second 3 weeks, <br>

4) then watch the arm diameter etc. continue to decrease for up to 6 months. </font></font></p><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana>

</font><font face=Verdana size=2><b>

</b></font><p><font face=Verdana size=2><b>Resource limitation OR body just take time to heal?</b></font><font face=Arial size=2><font face=Verdana> 

There may be some limited body resource for LLLT. It appears that there may be 

some limited resource. LLLT appears to be limited in either the body’s ability 

to create a resource (growth factor?) or distribute a resource. This resource 

limitation would account for a limitation of joules per square cm, even when 98% 

of the area is not illuminated. It would also account for a limited number of 

treatments per week – otherwise could instead of doing 3 treatments per week 

could do ay 20 treatments per week.</font></font></p><font face=Arial size=2>

healing - strongly indicated in the literature.<br>

<p>

<a href=http://www.walt.nu/scientific-secretary-report/promotion-of-walt-and-low-level-laser-therapy.html>

Review about LLLT in neck pain</a> clipped  "A more positive attitude can be found in the 

published neck pain review of the Bone and Joint Decade 2000-10 Task Force 

(Hurwitz et al., Spine. 2008 Feb 15;33(4 Suppl):S123-52.) They were only able to 

identify five out of the existing 17 randomized placebo-controlled LLLT trials 

in neck pain. In this systematic review the results showed that LLLT was one of 

three effective therapies for other than whiplash-associated neck pain. Still, 

the conclusion manages to miss out this important finding and only mentions the 

other two interventions. So again, two steps forward and one step back."</p>
